english:
  title: A Preface to Poems on the Plaque 'Pine Spring Serenity' by Ling, a Buddhist Monk from Japan
  author: Gwon Chae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Japan, situated at the eastern edge of the world, is a land of simple governance and pure people. Therefore its customs greatly honor the Buddha, and those who seek the Way travel to various lands under the guise of embassies. Since the Tang and Song dynasties, such were monks like Gyeongryeon, Jeogseo, and Yeongyae. When our Prince first ascended the throne, monks like Ni and Umunji came in succession, all versed in poetry. Now Ling, seeking Buddhist teachings, has served as an envoy to our realm three times over four years, from the year of the Water Rabbit to the year of the Wood Snake. The Prince, moved by his sincerity, commanded the officials to greet him beyond the gates and elevated his provisions and honors. The monk is young yet learned, serene of spirit and spare of frame, radiant and refined as ice held in jade.

    One day, presenting his plaque reading "Pine Spring Serenity," he entreated the scholars of court: "In the year I received the honor of your seal script, I have treasured it well. I humbly ask that you each compose a poem to complete this gift." The court's literary masters all composed, and I was asked to provide this preface.

    I reflect that each person's affections follow their nature. Tao Yuanming loved chrysanthemums for their reclusive spirit; lovers of willows prize their five benefits. Wang Huizhi cherished bamboo, and the Buddhist master Yuangong loved lotus—each had their reasons. What then does this monk intend by naming his dwelling "Pine Spring Serenity"?

    From the Confucian perspective, the Sage spoke of pine trees as steadfast through winter's trials, and of springs as never ceasing their flow day or night. Does the monk draw from such meanings? Or does he find in these forms an echo of the way of purity and perfect emptiness? I imagine it thus: in some remote hermitage among a thousand peaks and ten thousand valleys, pine wind caresses the face and spring water clarifies the mind, washing away all turbulent heat. Such a realm of coolness cannot be captured in mere words.

    Behold the pine's verdant trunk, defiant against snow and frost, enduring through all four seasons and a thousand years with leaves unfallen—is this not like the monk's attainment of adamantine strength that cannot be shaken? And the chill, living waters, flowing like jade, stretching a single stream across a thousand leagues without obstacle or stagnation—is this not like the monk's opening of the true source and entry into the subtle realm of enlightenment?

    When I observe this monk in his service, his words carry no error, his deportment in embassy is propriety itself. All his movements follow the proper form. Truly, he embodies what it means to speak as a Mohist yet live as a Confucian. Through him, our nation's rites, music, culture, and virtue reach across to his people, forging a bond of friendship and peace between our lands that will endure, without doubt, through ten thousand generations.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The four years span from 1452 (Year of the Water Rabbit) to 1455 (Year of the Wood Snake), during the reign of King Sejo of Joseon.
  - key: ''
    value: 'Ling''s plaque ''Pine Spring Serenity'' (松泉幽) plays on Buddhist symbolism: the pine represents steadfastness and longevity, while the spring represents clarity and the unobstructed flow of enlightenment.'
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to speaking as a Mohist while acting as a Confucian suggests a harmony between Buddhist principles and proper conduct in the secular realm.
  - key: ''
    value: Gyeongryeon, Jeogseo, and Yeongyae were historical Buddhist monks who traveled between Japan and China during the Tang and Song dynasties.
